1
00:00:06,794 --> 00:00:07,895
So, are you ready?

2
00:00:07,915 --> 00:00:07,975
Yes!

3
00:00:10,376 --> 00:00:10,756
Alright.

4
00:00:11,856 --> 00:00:15,778
So, welcome to SimCity Build It.

5
00:00:16,479 --> 00:00:19,620
What did I learn as a game designer?

6
00:00:21,301 --> 00:00:25,903
My name is Petri Ikonen and I come from Track20.

7
00:00:26,363 --> 00:00:28,444
I'm creative director there

8
00:00:29,405 --> 00:00:34,887
and Track20 is EA's mobile studio in Helsinki, Finland.

9
00:00:36,770 --> 00:00:42,312
And first, I will very briefly talk about my background a bit.

10
00:00:43,172 --> 00:00:47,753
So I changed to games industry 2003.

11
00:00:49,293 --> 00:00:52,954
Before that, I worked in field of theater and drama

12
00:00:52,994 --> 00:00:56,055
as an actor, director, script writer.

13
00:00:56,715 --> 00:00:58,395
But then I jumped into games.

14
00:00:59,016 --> 00:01:01,176
And I have not regretted a day.

15
00:01:01,556 --> 00:01:03,437
It's been a great industry to work for.

16
00:01:04,580 --> 00:01:09,726
So I joined Sumea 2003.

17
00:01:09,867 --> 00:01:13,311
Sumea was a very small startup in Helsinki.

18
00:01:14,290 --> 00:01:18,331
And then very quickly it was acquired by Digital Chocolate.

19
00:01:18,791 --> 00:01:22,913
And those first years we were creating Java mobile games.

20
00:01:23,713 --> 00:01:24,974
Very different times.

21
00:01:25,474 --> 00:01:27,054
Very big restrictions.

22
00:01:27,655 --> 00:01:29,195
Very small screens.

23
00:01:29,375 --> 00:01:31,276
Very small build sizes.

24
00:01:32,156 --> 00:01:35,357
The business was controlled by operators.

25
00:01:36,358 --> 00:01:37,918
And it was premium model.

26
00:01:39,419 --> 00:01:42,460
And then came the first big change.

27
00:01:43,431 --> 00:01:45,693
touch screen, app store.

28
00:01:46,694 --> 00:01:50,418
And we really, as game developers, we needed, again,

29
00:01:50,498 --> 00:01:55,243
to learn something new, learn a totally new type of

30
00:01:58,626 --> 00:02:00,928
interface, touch controls.

31
00:02:02,510 --> 00:02:03,651
Very interesting times.

32
00:02:03,751 --> 00:02:08,316
And then came even bigger revolution, free to play.

33
00:02:09,583 --> 00:02:15,267
I was working as an executive producer in multiple Facebook games.

34
00:02:15,888 --> 00:02:19,431
And I had to learn free-to-play as early as 2009, 2010.

35
00:02:20,832 --> 00:02:28,458
And it was tough, but I'm really grateful that I had to do that.

36
00:02:28,918 --> 00:02:35,784
And also, I had to learn what it means to run games as a service.

37
00:02:37,597 --> 00:02:40,718
So that's my background in very briefly.

38
00:02:41,058 --> 00:02:44,520
And all these years I've been really concentrating on game

39
00:02:44,560 --> 00:02:46,621
design, because I love game design.

40
00:02:46,861 --> 00:02:47,481
And it's tough.

41
00:02:48,541 --> 00:02:52,043
So at the moment, I'm working at Track 20.

42
00:02:52,763 --> 00:02:54,444
It's a very small studio.

43
00:02:55,264 --> 00:02:56,885
There's less than 50 people.

44
00:02:57,956 --> 00:03:00,438
But we have 17 nationalities.

45
00:03:00,998 --> 00:03:04,160
And that one, it's a very big asset for us,

46
00:03:04,660 --> 00:03:08,082
to have all those people from all over the world

47
00:03:08,563 --> 00:03:09,763
to working together.

48
00:03:10,044 --> 00:03:13,166
And that's one big thing that you can have in your studio,

49
00:03:13,706 --> 00:03:16,768
because we are creating games for global market.

50
00:03:18,409 --> 00:03:20,550
And then the game, SimCity build it.

51
00:03:23,108 --> 00:03:26,891
This was a very tough project, very difficult to design.

52
00:03:28,031 --> 00:03:32,634
The game was soft launched October 2014, and then we went worldwide December 2014.

53
00:03:33,214 --> 00:03:35,115
And it's been a big success.

54
00:03:42,298 --> 00:03:46,520
We have a very big amount of users every day playing the

55
00:03:46,560 --> 00:03:46,880
game.

56
00:03:47,320 --> 00:03:52,222
It's been on top crossing charts since, and I'm very

57
00:03:52,282 --> 00:03:53,183
proud of this game.

58
00:03:54,063 --> 00:03:56,524
But the project was a very difficult one.

59
00:03:58,025 --> 00:03:59,285
So this is the overview.

60
00:03:59,986 --> 00:04:05,488
I'm going to talk about four very tricky design challenges

61
00:04:06,308 --> 00:04:09,469
that I did face during this project.

62
00:04:10,570 --> 00:04:15,074
And I try to explain also that what do I think that I learned.

63
00:04:16,575 --> 00:04:19,597
And then after that, I will kind of think that, hey,

64
00:04:20,057 --> 00:04:25,521
why did we succeed even though the challenges were so tough?

65
00:04:28,243 --> 00:04:29,204
So let's go further.

66
00:04:29,544 --> 00:04:33,547
First design challenge, classic IP.

67
00:04:37,043 --> 00:04:38,905
It's a huge IP, you know it.

68
00:04:39,125 --> 00:04:43,469
The game is older than 25 years.

69
00:04:44,510 --> 00:04:47,732
And it's been, of course, the main platform has been PC.

70
00:04:48,873 --> 00:04:51,075
And then we got that as a project.

71
00:04:51,716 --> 00:04:55,639
And you can think that what kind of excitement it is.

72
00:04:56,600 --> 00:05:00,363
So the whole team is really excited that, hey, we are the

73
00:05:00,524 --> 00:05:02,926
ones who will be creating the next SimCity.

74
00:05:03,909 --> 00:05:05,751
And you get all that inspiration.

75
00:05:06,351 --> 00:05:08,153
And you are so kind of that, yes!

76
00:05:09,254 --> 00:05:13,898
But then, very quickly, after a couple of weeks of the project,

77
00:05:14,418 --> 00:05:16,440
you start to realize that, oops!

78
00:05:17,701 --> 00:05:20,183
This will be a very tricky one.

79
00:05:20,743 --> 00:05:22,445
This will be so hard.

80
00:05:23,225 --> 00:05:25,968
And a couple of weeks more and you are that,

81
00:05:26,488 --> 00:05:28,230
oops! Can we make this?

82
00:05:29,337 --> 00:05:33,698
And also what you understand that, whoo, there is so much

83
00:05:34,278 --> 00:05:38,700
fun fans out there, and they have huge expectations.

84
00:05:39,540 --> 00:05:41,141
They are expecting something.

85
00:05:41,621 --> 00:05:43,362
Are we able to deliver that?

86
00:05:44,282 --> 00:05:48,283
So that was kind of the first big design challenge that I,

87
00:05:49,004 --> 00:05:51,584
or what we faced as a team.

88
00:05:52,145 --> 00:05:54,085
So what did I learn?

89
00:05:54,786 --> 00:05:55,326
I think that

90
00:05:57,879 --> 00:06:04,422
We really needed to reimagine what is SimCity on mobile.

91
00:06:04,862 --> 00:06:09,245
So it's not enough to kind of take the things from the PC

92
00:06:09,305 --> 00:06:13,427
game and somehow adapt or port those.

93
00:06:13,647 --> 00:06:15,769
You have to really reimagine.

94
00:06:16,109 --> 00:06:20,331
It meant that we had to kind of redesign the

95
00:06:20,371 --> 00:06:21,852
whole game from scratch.

96
00:06:23,215 --> 00:06:27,679
So definitely the platform is what defines how the game

97
00:06:27,719 --> 00:06:28,279
should play.

98
00:06:28,599 --> 00:06:32,822
So you can't take PC stuff and just put it on mobile.

99
00:06:34,063 --> 00:06:37,686
And then one thing that I think fortunately we managed

100
00:06:37,726 --> 00:06:41,949
to do was that because the expectations are high, you

101
00:06:41,989 --> 00:06:46,553
have to really manage those expectations, communicate to

102
00:06:46,573 --> 00:06:48,794
the fans that this is a mobile game.

103
00:06:50,009 --> 00:06:54,891
This is a free-to-play game, so that they don't think that

104
00:06:54,971 --> 00:06:58,933
there is a next SimCity 2000 coming again on mobile.

105
00:07:01,454 --> 00:07:02,755
Second design challenge.

106
00:07:03,395 --> 00:07:04,555
This was even tougher.

107
00:07:05,596 --> 00:07:06,356
Free-to-play.

108
00:07:06,877 --> 00:07:10,498
I think free-to-play is very difficult to design.

109
00:07:11,139 --> 00:07:15,221
It's much more difficult than old premium model, at

110
00:07:15,281 --> 00:07:16,041
least for me.

111
00:07:17,942 --> 00:07:18,062
And.

112
00:07:19,145 --> 00:07:22,407
When we started the project, we thought that, yes, it's easy.

113
00:07:22,427 --> 00:07:27,670
We just kind of follow the very typical free-to-play

114
00:07:27,730 --> 00:07:28,470
conventions.

115
00:07:29,391 --> 00:07:34,294
And what we did, we started to try energy mechanics, builder

116
00:07:34,334 --> 00:07:38,936
mechanics, and more or less all those failed, because the

117
00:07:39,056 --> 00:07:44,239
pacing of the game would have been really slow very quickly.

118
00:07:44,784 --> 00:07:48,987
And we realized that the game would be very boring with those mechanics.

119
00:07:49,268 --> 00:07:53,772
And that was actually the reason that after multiple prototypes we decided that

120
00:07:54,232 --> 00:07:59,076
okay, the crafting mechanics is the one that we will follow in the core loop.

121
00:08:01,839 --> 00:08:08,024
So, what did I really learn about free-to-play in this project was that

122
00:08:08,785 --> 00:08:10,747
I think that there is a big...

123
00:08:11,455 --> 00:08:15,117
big change at the moment, or even kind of a change of

124
00:08:15,237 --> 00:08:15,777
paradigm.

125
00:08:16,178 --> 00:08:20,200
And I think that we shouldn't pinch players too much.

126
00:08:20,821 --> 00:08:26,084
We shouldn't pinch players and say that you either wait, or

127
00:08:26,144 --> 00:08:26,945
then you pay.

128
00:08:27,185 --> 00:08:31,988
We should be much more gentle and kind of develop games that

129
00:08:32,108 --> 00:08:36,751
are fun to play, and then offer even more fun by saying

130
00:08:36,811 --> 00:08:38,692
that, hey, you love this game.

131
00:08:38,732 --> 00:08:39,893
You enjoy this game.

132
00:08:40,638 --> 00:08:46,039
you are willing to spend weeks and months playing this game.

133
00:08:46,179 --> 00:08:48,820
So perhaps you should invest some money

134
00:08:48,960 --> 00:08:50,720
and enjoy it even more.

135
00:08:51,320 --> 00:08:54,721
So we should really kind of swap the whole thinking,

136
00:08:55,181 --> 00:08:59,222
not pinching players, instead offering them more value.

137
00:08:59,882 --> 00:09:03,803
Offering them things that they can be more efficient

138
00:09:04,163 --> 00:09:05,423
and enjoy the game more.

139
00:09:10,393 --> 00:09:16,756
Third design challenge. Mobile user experience, mobile UI.

140
00:09:21,618 --> 00:09:29,542
SimCity PC version, and kind of a tradition of SimCity is, it's lots of information.

141
00:09:30,818 --> 00:09:35,179
big PC screen, numbers, lots of numbers.

142
00:09:35,600 --> 00:09:37,240
And of course, that's very crucial.

143
00:09:37,700 --> 00:09:40,521
As a mayor, you need all that information

144
00:09:40,882 --> 00:09:43,783
so that you can make meaningful choices

145
00:09:44,103 --> 00:09:45,603
based on that information.

146
00:09:46,264 --> 00:09:49,565
And what we found out immediately was that, oops,

147
00:09:50,745 --> 00:09:53,326
we want to support very small screens.

148
00:09:54,066 --> 00:09:58,108
How are we able to fit all that information

149
00:09:58,188 --> 00:09:59,328
on a small screen?

150
00:10:00,386 --> 00:10:04,188
And then, very quickly, we understood also that it's very

151
00:10:04,288 --> 00:10:09,090
difficult to find very natural, easy ways to control

152
00:10:09,130 --> 00:10:11,251
your city with touch controls.

153
00:10:11,911 --> 00:10:13,872
How do you do all the build actions?

154
00:10:15,552 --> 00:10:18,334
And then we started to think that, hey, how do

155
00:10:18,354 --> 00:10:19,434
you play the game?

156
00:10:20,254 --> 00:10:24,076
Classical SimCity PC thing is that you play

157
00:10:24,516 --> 00:10:25,657
very long sessions.

158
00:10:25,857 --> 00:10:29,318
But now mobile playing, it's about very short sessions.

159
00:10:30,305 --> 00:10:34,387
So our players play perhaps five, six, seven sessions per

160
00:10:34,427 --> 00:10:37,869
day, but each session is just two, three minutes long.

161
00:10:38,529 --> 00:10:43,271
So we really needed to think our kind of the whole user

162
00:10:43,411 --> 00:10:48,014
experience and pacing of the game to support typical mobile

163
00:10:48,174 --> 00:10:52,756
usage instead of that old PC thing.

164
00:10:55,857 --> 00:10:56,778
So what did I learn?

165
00:10:57,498 --> 00:10:59,479
I think that on mobile.

166
00:11:00,643 --> 00:11:02,264
Design equals UI.

167
00:11:02,544 --> 00:11:06,705
And what do I mean with that is that if your user interface

168
00:11:06,785 --> 00:11:10,086
is not able to communicate the design,

169
00:11:10,827 --> 00:11:12,367
the design is worthless.

170
00:11:13,827 --> 00:11:17,749
So you have to always think that is the UI able to

171
00:11:17,809 --> 00:11:18,509
communicate?

172
00:11:18,569 --> 00:11:21,130
Is the gameplay able to communicate the design?

173
00:11:22,430 --> 00:11:28,792
And most of the mobile games, they are very, uh,

174
00:11:29,683 --> 00:11:36,791
UI heavy and information heavy and we had that kind of very big trap that all that information

175
00:11:37,352 --> 00:11:39,374
Do we spam all that?

176
00:11:40,235 --> 00:11:44,780
But fortunately we understood that yes, we have to simplify simplify

177
00:11:45,634 --> 00:11:48,995
And also, abandon always conventions from old platforms.

178
00:11:49,415 --> 00:11:52,215
So what easily happened was that I was very excited

179
00:11:52,315 --> 00:11:55,476
something that was on PC game.

180
00:11:55,536 --> 00:11:58,656
And then I wanted to more or less copy that on mobile.

181
00:11:58,916 --> 00:12:01,177
And every time it failed.

182
00:12:01,557 --> 00:12:02,797
So it was totally stupid.

183
00:12:04,517 --> 00:12:08,118
And also, what we learned about the production that when

184
00:12:08,178 --> 00:12:12,139
you want to create great touch controls, it will take time.

185
00:12:12,299 --> 00:12:14,879
It will take lots of iteration rounds.

186
00:12:19,257 --> 00:12:21,897
Then the fourth design challenge.

187
00:12:23,297 --> 00:12:24,598
Open-ended simulation.

188
00:12:25,058 --> 00:12:30,299
I think one core thing in SimCity is really the

189
00:12:30,359 --> 00:12:35,680
simulation and that it's very open-ended and it's sandboxy.

190
00:12:35,780 --> 00:12:39,141
And as a mayor, you can do whatever you like.

191
00:12:39,541 --> 00:12:42,901
And you can really experiment and be creative.

192
00:12:43,122 --> 00:12:46,082
And we want this to support that core idea.

193
00:12:47,583 --> 00:12:51,371
And we ran, kind of, we faced lots of problems.

194
00:12:51,631 --> 00:12:53,816
For example, what is time?

195
00:12:54,479 --> 00:12:55,699
What is concept of time?

196
00:12:56,320 --> 00:12:57,760
We have real time.

197
00:12:57,840 --> 00:12:59,380
We have device time.

198
00:12:59,881 --> 00:13:03,782
Then we have the city time, where the day is just perhaps

199
00:13:04,282 --> 00:13:08,423
10 minutes long, and the night is a couple of minutes.

200
00:13:08,563 --> 00:13:11,144
And we were kind of confused.

201
00:13:12,004 --> 00:13:15,025
How should we kind of think the whole simulation?

202
00:13:15,065 --> 00:13:18,086
That is it following the city time, or real time, or device

203
00:13:18,146 --> 00:13:18,366
time?

204
00:13:19,471 --> 00:13:23,254
And then we started to think that, hey, what happens if you close the app?

205
00:13:23,975 --> 00:13:25,997
Is the simulation still running there?

206
00:13:27,218 --> 00:13:33,663
And what happens when you come back after two hours, two weeks, two months?

207
00:13:34,804 --> 00:13:36,586
Is the whole city destroyed?

208
00:13:36,666 --> 00:13:40,649
Is it just ruins or every building is on fire?

209
00:13:41,634 --> 00:13:50,961
And we didn't want to punish the player too much, so we created very exact rules so that the simulation slows down.

210
00:13:51,501 --> 00:13:59,607
And yes, there has happened some things in the city when you are away, but when you come back, you see that, oh, there has been something.

211
00:14:00,328 --> 00:14:06,612
You can understand what has happened, you can react on those, but we can't punish the player too much.

212
00:14:07,553 --> 00:14:11,235
And also, a very interesting problem was that, how is your

213
00:14:11,275 --> 00:14:12,376
city talking to you?

214
00:14:12,936 --> 00:14:15,998
Now, simulation engine is running under the hood.

215
00:14:16,778 --> 00:14:21,161
But if we can't communicate those things to players, it's

216
00:14:21,241 --> 00:14:22,682
basically worthless there.

217
00:14:23,142 --> 00:14:28,165
So we had to implement multiple parallel systems how

218
00:14:28,205 --> 00:14:30,306
to make the city communicate.

219
00:14:30,847 --> 00:14:33,888
So SimCitizens, they are having speech bubbles and

220
00:14:33,988 --> 00:14:34,669
thought bubbles.

221
00:14:36,004 --> 00:14:42,111
each service data layer has information what's happening in that particular service.

222
00:14:42,491 --> 00:14:46,816
And then if you tap on any residential building, you again get information that

223
00:14:47,697 --> 00:14:50,761
how is that particular building doing.

224
00:14:52,422 --> 00:14:53,403
So what did I learn?

225
00:14:53,944 --> 00:14:54,325
I think...

226
00:14:55,334 --> 00:14:59,677
Simulation under the hood is a great thing, and it's very fascinating.

227
00:15:00,297 --> 00:15:09,544
But if you implement it, make sure that you are able also to pass that information to players.

228
00:15:10,084 --> 00:15:13,087
Because if it's just under the hood, who cares?

229
00:15:14,148 --> 00:15:17,490
So don't overdo. I think that was a big lesson for me that...

230
00:15:18,989 --> 00:15:21,591
Because what happened to us was that we created a big

231
00:15:21,631 --> 00:15:25,052
simulation, and then we realized that, oh, we don't

232
00:15:25,132 --> 00:15:26,933
get any information on that.

233
00:15:27,394 --> 00:15:31,816
And it was quick to implement the simulation under the hood,

234
00:15:31,856 --> 00:15:35,458
but very time consuming and difficult to implement all the

235
00:15:35,518 --> 00:15:38,780
systems that then pass the information to the player.

236
00:15:42,002 --> 00:15:45,824
Those were typical problems that we faced.

237
00:15:47,218 --> 00:15:49,940
from design point of view during the project.

238
00:15:51,082 --> 00:15:52,163
But we did succeed.

239
00:15:53,204 --> 00:15:54,545
And why did we succeed?

240
00:15:54,985 --> 00:15:58,329
That's something that I've been thinking a lot.

241
00:16:00,251 --> 00:16:04,635
One thing that I'm very proud of is our team culture.

242
00:16:08,787 --> 00:16:13,511
There is a very big trust there.

243
00:16:14,012 --> 00:16:17,755
And then there is also a very big passion to create games.

244
00:16:18,415 --> 00:16:22,218
And then there is this kind of very Finnish culture thing

245
00:16:22,278 --> 00:16:23,259
that never give up.

246
00:16:23,819 --> 00:16:27,883
You know, living up there in north, if you give up,

247
00:16:28,443 --> 00:16:31,706
especially during winter time, you'll die very quickly.

248
00:16:34,262 --> 00:16:36,424
So that was kind of in our DNA.

249
00:16:36,444 --> 00:16:41,568
And how, I mean, that however, I mean, that the project was so

250
00:16:41,628 --> 00:16:45,071
hard, and we redesigned and redesigned and re-implemented.

251
00:16:45,611 --> 00:16:47,152
But no one left the team.

252
00:16:47,253 --> 00:16:49,714
No one said that let's quit or anything.

253
00:16:50,235 --> 00:16:52,377
So we kind of kept on iterating.

254
00:16:52,737 --> 00:16:54,899
And kind of the mentality was all the time

255
00:16:54,939 --> 00:16:55,919
that we won't give up.

256
00:16:56,380 --> 00:16:57,160
We will do this.

